## Steps to Reproduce

1. Start-debug any flutter app in Android Studio
2. Click the stop button

**Expected results:** IDE stops debugging and the app terminates

**Actual results:** IDE stops debugging but the app keeps working on the device

Command line `flutter run` and then 'q' works so it has to be an IDE/plugin issue.

<details>

comment_data.body:
I cannot reproduce this. I suspect the problem has been fixed in the latest plugin. Please update Android Studio, the plugins, and Flutter SDK. Let us know if the problem is fixed.

It is possible that your Flutter SDK is so old that it does not work with more recent plugins. There have been some changes to the communication protocol used between the plugin and the flutter tool.

No, this is device-specific

What command does the plugin use for termination? Is there a 'shell' involved?
https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/58670
@jacob314 @devoncarew Can you think of any way a device dependence could cause the IDE to not stop the app after the Stop button is clicked? I suspect this is an issue in the Flutter tool.

@duzenko It's been a while since I looked at the code for the Flutter tool, so I don't know if there is a shell involved, but there might be. The IDE communicates with the tool using a JSON protocol that is enabled by the --machine option used in the `flutter run` command. We may need to make changes similar to what you did to get logcat working.
I re-opened https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/64241 with a comment stating why.

Lately, I've been getting the complete opposite - my app is stopping, but IntelliJ is acting like it's not. The run button continues to show a green dot, and nothing happens when I press it again (other than going grey for a second).

Closing and opening the project seems to reset it, but upon closing, I need to press "disconnect", "cancel", and "disconnect" again.

Could this be related, or should I open a new issue here?

@hacker1024 Please open a new issue. If you have a sample project that reproduces the problem please include it. Also include the output of `flutter doctor --verbose` and which device you are using. This sounds like it might also be an issue with the flutter cmd line tool, but it might also be in the IDE.
@duzenko This is a dup of flutter/flutter#64241

title: Debugger: the stop button does not stop the app #64241
